1. Chaos in science

In mathematics, chaos doesn’t mean randomness.

In Chaos theory it means:
	•	deterministic rules
	•	extremely sensitive to initial conditions

A classic example is the Lorenz attractor — a system governed by simple equations but whose trajectories diverge rapidly.

Two nearly identical starting points lead to dramatically different outcomes.

So the modern scientific view is actually close to what you said:

chaos is not lack of order — it’s order that is too sensitive or complex for easy prediction.

⸻

2. Hidden structure inside “chaos”

When researchers study chaotic systems they often discover unexpected constants and invariants.

For example the Feigenbaum constant appears in many unrelated chaotic systems.

Different systems — fluids, electronic circuits, chemical reactions — show the same ratio when their oscillations double.

That means even chaos contains deep structure.

